  {
    "chunk_id": "docling_exam_paper_en-file-putnam-archive_2003_Solutions_2003s_page_001_17",
    "text": "In terms of the function",
    "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
    "bbox": [
      0.5582706779317022,
      0.2805059524116231,
      0.7142857141265683,
      0.29216269844336923
    ],
    "page": "exam_paper_en-file-putnam-archive_2003_Solutions_2003s_page_001",
    "order": 8
  },
  {
    "chunk_id": "docling_exam_paper_en-file-putnam-archive_2003_Solutions_2003s_page_001_5",
    "text": "However, there is a unique integer a satisfying these inequalities, namely a1 = n/k. Moreover, once a1 is fixed, there are k different possibilities for the sum a1 + az+... + ak: if i is the last integer such that aj = a1, then the sum equals ka, + (i - 1). The possible values of i are 1,...,k, and exactly one of these sums comes out equal to n, proving our claim.",
    "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
    "bbox": [
      0.12593984984900555,
      0.3008432539244701,
      0.49060151109241035,
      0.40116279034130087
    ],
    "page": "exam_paper_en-file-putnam-archive_2003_Solutions_2003s_page_001",
    "order": 9
  },
  {
    "chunk_id": "docling_exam_paper_en-file-putnam-archive_2003_Solutions_2003s_page_001_18",
    "text": "",
    "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
    "bbox": [
      0.6560150414260569,
      0.3080357142460434,
      0.7800751862055217,
