  {
    "chunk_id": "docling_exam_paper_en-file-putnam-archive_2003_Solutions_2003s_page_001_6",
    "text": "Note: In summary, there is a unique partition of n with k terms that is \"as equally spaced as possible\". One can also obtain essentially the same construction inductively: except for the all-ones sum, each partition of n is obtained by \"augmenting\" a unique partition of n - 1.",
    "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
    "bbox": [
      0.12781954002757723,
      0.40697674397852407,
      0.49060151260400175,
      0.4781976744480747
    ],
    "page": "exam_paper_en-file-putnam-archive_2003_Solutions_2003s_page_001",
    "order": 13
  },
  {
    "chunk_id": "docling_exam_paper_en-file-putnam-archive_2003_Solutions_2003s_page_001_21",
    "text": "This will follow from Jensen's inequality if we can verify that fis a convex function; it is enough to check that f\"(x) > 0 for all x. In fact,",
    "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
    "bbox": [
      0.5563909931948295,
      0.4186046510642799,
      0.9210526249442679,
      0.46230158747638517
    ],
    "page": "exam_paper_en-file-putnam-archive_2003_Solutions_2003s_page_001",
    "order": 14
  },
  {
    "chunk_id": "docling_exam_paper_en-file-putnam-archive_2003_Solutions_2003s_page_001_22",
    "text": "",
    "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
    "bbox": [
      0.6240601528062293,
      0.47383720948461194,
      0.8082706769971806,
      0.5014880952797672
    ],
    "page": "exam_paper_en-file-putnam-archive_2003_Solutions_2003s_page_001",
    "order": 15
  },
  {
    "chunk_id": "docling_exam_paper_en-file-putnam-archive_2003_Solutions_2003s_page_001_7",
    "text": "A2 First solution: Assume without loss of generality that ait bi > 0 for each i (otherwise both sides of the desired inequality are zero). Then the AM-GM inequality gives",
    "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
    "bbox": [
      0.10338346531703443,
      0.48982558127866954,
      0.49060151109241035,
      0.5319940474985344
    ],
    "page": "exam_paper_en-file-putnam-archive_2003_Solutions_2003s_page_001",
    "order": 16
  },
  {
    "chunk_id": "docling_exam_paper_en-file-putnam-archive_2003_Solutions_2003s_page_001_23",
    "text": "is an increasing function of x, so f\" (x) > 0 and Jensen's inequality thus yields the desired result. (As long as the aj are all positive, equality holds when s1 = ... = Sn, i.e., when the vectors (a1,..,an) and (b1,..., bn). Of course other equality cases crop up if some of the aj vanish, i.e., if a1 = b1 = 0.)",
    "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
    "bbox": [
      0.5563909685990056,
      0.5145348841742029,
      0.9210526264636915,
      0.6017441857856154
    ],
    "page": "exam_paper_en-file-putnam-archive_2003_Solutions_2003s_page_001",
    "order": 17
  },
  {
    "chunk_id": "docling_exam_paper_en-file-putnam-archive_2003_Solutions_2003s_page_001_8",
    "text": "",
    "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
    "bbox": [
